Good posts, Swanson.  Very good info, I thought.  And no surprise the heavy-contributing companies are exempt, not to mention the political parties themselves.<br>
<br>
From USA TODAY again, headline in today's Money section: <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Do-not-call list thwarted again</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I'll summarize what it sez.  Guess a different federal judge struck down the list again within an hour of the legislation passing.  As Swanson said, it is unfair because it singles out some types of telemarketers over others, thus violating the free speech rights of the ones restricted.  Sounds like the judge's opinion is either no one should be allowed to call, or everyone has to be allowed to call.<br>
<br>
A related article on the following page said that some websites posted the first ruling judge's home and office numbers and people have been totally spamming him since the decision came out.  USA Today was unable to reach him for comment, lol.<br>
<br>
I hate telemarketers as much as the next guy, but as it stands it IS unfair that political parties, charities, etc. are exempt.  The rules need to be the same for everyone using telephone solicitation.  It will be interesting to see how this all shakes out in the end.<br>
<br>
Some other attorney specializing in telemarketing clients said she thinks this will delay but not kill the no call list.  She thinks too much interest has been shown by voters so some compromise will be reached eventually. <p>Axaroth<br>
65 Storm Warden<br>
